ce code could then use the dependencies like this:","pos":[10146,10205]},{"content":"Note that all of the .NET Framework and .NET Standard targets have names recognized by the compiler:","pos":[10348,10448]},{"content":"As mentioned above, if you are targeting a PCL, then you will have to specify a build definition for the compiler to understand.","pos":[11022,11150]},{"content":"There is no default definition that the compiler can use.","pos":[11151,11208]},{"pos":[11214,11251],"content":"Using <ph id=\"ph1\">`project.json`</ph> in Visual Studio","linkify":"Using `project.json` in Visual Studio","source":"Using `project.json` in Visual Studio"},{"pos":[11253,11316],"content":"You have two options for using <ph id=\"ph1\">`project.json`</ph> in Visual Studio:","source":"You have two options for using `project.json` in Visual Studio:"},{"content":"A new xproj project type.","pos":[11321,11346]},{"content":"A retargeted PCL project which supports .NET Standard.","pos":[11350,11404]},{"content":"There are different benefits and drawbacks for each.","pos":[11406,11458]},{"pos":[11465,11494],"content":"When to Pick an Xproj Project","linkify":"When to Pick an Xproj Project","nodes":[{"content":"When to Pick an Xproj Project","pos":[0,29]}]},{"pos":[11496,11785],"content":"The new Xproj project system in Visual Studio utilizes the capabilities of the <ph id=\"ph1\">`project.json`</ph>-based project model to offer two major features over existing project types: seamless multitargeting by building multiple assemblies and the ability to directly generate a NuGet package on build.","source":"The new Xproj project system in Visual Studio utilizes the capabilities of the `project.json`-based project model to offer two major features over existing project types: seamless multitargeting by building multiple assemblies and the ability to directly generate a NuGet package on build."},{"content":"However, it comes at the cost of lacking certain features you may use, such as:","pos":