ty of Your Code","linkify":"Determining the Portability of Your Code","nodes":[{"content":"Determining the Portability of Your Code","pos":[0,40]}]},{"content":"The next step is to run the API Portability Analyzer (ApiPort) to generate a portability report that you can begin to analyze.","pos":[14059,14185]},{"content":"You'll need to make sure you understand the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>API Portability tool (ApiPort)<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/Microsoft/dotnet-apiport/blob/master/docs/HowTo/)</ept> and can generate portability reports for targeting .NET Core.","pos":[14187,14394],"source":"You'll need to make sure you understand the [API Portability tool (ApiPort)](https://github.com/Microsoft/dotnet-apiport/blob/master/docs/HowTo/) and can generate portability reports for targeting .NET Core."},{"content":"How you do this will likely vary based on your needs and personal tastes.","pos":[14395,14468]},{"content":"What follows are a few different approaches - you may find yourself mixing each approach depending on how your code is structured.","pos":[14469,14599]},{"pos":[14605,14640],"content":"Dealing Primarily with the Compiler","linkify":"Dealing Primarily with the Compiler","nodes":[{"content":"Dealing Primarily with the Compiler","pos":[0,35]}]},{"content":"This approach may be the best for small projects or projects which don't use many .NET Framework APIs.","pos":[14642,14744]},{"content":"The approach is very simple:","pos":[14745,14773]},{"content":"Optionally run ApiPort on your project.","pos":[14778,14817]},{"content":"If ApiPort was ran, take a quick glance at the report.","pos":[14821,14875]},{"content":"Copy all of your code over into a new .NET Core project.","pos":[14879,14935]},{"content":"Work out compiler errors until it compiles, referring to the portability report if needed.","pos":[14939,15029]},{"content":"Repeat as needed.","pos":[15033,15050]},{"content":"Although this approach is very unstructured, the code-focused approach can lead 