1]}]},{"content":"This approach may be best for larger and more complex projects, where restructuring of code or rewriting certain areas may be necessary to support .NET Core.","pos":[16354,16511]},{"content":"The approach is as follows:","pos":[16512,16539]},{"content":"Run ApiPort on a project.","pos":[16544,16569]},{"content":"Understand where in your code each non-portable type is being used and how that affects overall portability.","pos":[16573,16681]},{"content":"a.","pos":[16686,16688]},{"content":"Understand the nature of those types.","pos":[16689,16726]},{"content":"Are they small in number, but used frequently?","pos":[16727,16773]},{"content":"Are they large in number, but used infrequently?","pos":[16774,16822]},{"content":"Is their use concentrated, or is it spread throughout your code?","pos":[16823,16887]},{"content":"b.","pos":[16895,16897]},{"content":"Is it easy to isolate code that isn't portable so you can deal with it more easily?","pos":[16898,16981]},{"content":"c.","pos":[16989,16991]},{"content":"Would you need to refactor your code?","pos":[16992,17029]},{"content":"d.","pos":[17037,17039]},{"content":"For those types which aren't portable, are there alternative APIs that accomplish the same task?","pos":[17040,17136]},{"content":"For example, if you're using the <ph id=\"ph1\">`WebClient`</ph> class, you may be able to use the <ph id=\"ph2\">`HttpClient`</ph> class instead.","pos":[17137,17243],"source":" For example, if you're using the `WebClient` class, you may be able to use the `HttpClient` class instead."},{"content":"e.","pos":[17251,17253]},{"content":"Are there different portable APIs you can use to accomplish a task, even if it's not a drop-in replacement?","pos":[17254,17361]},{"content":"For example, if you're using <ph id=\"ph1\">`XmlSchema`</ph> to help parse XML, but you don't require XML schema discovery, you could use <ph id=\"ph2\">`System.Linq.Xml`</ph> APIs and hand-parse the data.","pos":[17362,17527],"source":" For example, if you're using `XmlSchema` to help parse XML, but you don't require XML schema discovery, you could use `System.Linq.Xml` APIs and hand-parse the data."},{"content":"If you have assemblies that are difficult to port, is it worth leaving them on .NET Framework for now?","pos":[17532,17634]},{"content":"Here are some things to consider:","pos":[17635,17668]},{"content":"a.","pos":[17673,17675]},{"content":"You may have some functionality in your library that's incompatible with .NET Core because it relies too heavily on .NET Framework- or Windows-specific functionality.","pos":[17676,17842]},{"content":"Is it worth leaving that functionality behind for now and releasing a .NET Core version of your library with less features for the time being?","pos":[17843,17985]},{"content":"b.","pos":[17993,17995]},{"content":"Would a refactor help here?","pos":[17996,18023]},{"content":"Is it reasonable to write your own implementation of an unavailable .NET Framework API?","pos":[18031,18118]},{"content":"You could consider instead copying, modifying, and using code from the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>.NET Framework Reference Source<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/Microsoft/referencesource)</ept>.","pos":[18123,18274],"source":"You could consider instead copying, modifying, and using code from the [.NET Framework Reference Source](https://github.com/Microsoft/referencesource)."},{"content":"It's licensed under the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>MIT License<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/Microsoft/referencesource/blob/master/LICENSE.txt)</ept>, so you have significant freedom in doing this.","pos":[18275,18430],"source":" It's licensed under the [MIT License](https://github.com/Microsoft/referencesource/blob/master/LICENSE.txt), so you have significant freedom in doing this."},{"content":"Just be sure to properly attribute Microsoft in your code!","pos":[18431,18489]},{"content":"Repeat this process as needed for different projects.","pos":[18497,18550]},{"content":"Once you have a plan, execute that plan.","pos":[18554,18594]},{"content":"The analysis phase could take some time depending on how large your codebase is.","pos":[18597,18677]},{"content":"Spending time in this phase to thoroughly understand the scope of changes needed and to develop a plan can save you a lot of time in the long run, particularly if you have a more complex codebase.","pos":[18678,18874]},{"content":"Your plan could involve making significant changes to your codebase while still targeting .NET Framework 4.6.2, making this a more structured version of the previous approach.","pos":[18876,19051]},{"content":"How you go about executing your plan will be dependent on your codebase.","pos":[19052,19124]},{"pos":[19130,19147],"content":"Mixing Approaches","linkify":"Mixing Approaches","nodes":[{"content":"Mixing Approaches","pos":[0,17]}]},{"content":"It's likely that you'll mix the above approaches on a per-project basis.","pos":[19149,19221]},{"content":"You should do what makes the most sense to you and for your codebase.","pos":[19222,19291]},{"pos":[19296,19314],"content":"Porting your Tests","linkify":"Porting your Tests","nodes":[{"content":"Porting your Tests","pos":[0,18]}]},{"content":"The best way to make sure everything works when you've ported your code is to test your code as you port it to .NET Core.","pos":[19316,19437]},{"content":"To do this, you'll need to use a testing framework that will build and run tests for .NET Core.","pos":[19438,19533]},{"content":"Currently, you have three options:","pos":[19534,19568]},{"pos":[19572,19605],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>xUnit<ept id=\"p1\">](https://xunit.github.io/)</ept>","source":"[xUnit](https://xunit.github.io/)"},{"pos":[19611,19690],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Getting Started<ept id=\"p1\">](http://xunit.github.io/docs/getting-started-dotnet-core.html)</ept>","source":"[Getting Started](http://xunit.github.io/docs/getting-started-dotnet-core.html)"},{"pos":[19696,19812],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Tool to convert an MSTest project to xUnit<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/dotnet/codeformatter/tree/master/src/XUnitConverter)</ept>","source":"[Tool to convert an MSTest project to xUnit](https://github.com/dotnet/codeformatter/tree/master/src/XUnitConverter)"},{"pos":[19815,19845],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>NUnit<ept id=\"p1\">](http://www.nunit.org/)</ept>","source":"[NUnit](http://www.nunit.org/)"},{"pos":[19850,19916],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Getting Started<ept id=\"p1\">](https://github.com/nunit/docs/wiki/Installation)</ept>","source":"[Getting Started](https://github.com/nunit/docs/wiki/Installation)"},{"pos":[19921,20036],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Blog post about migrating from MSTest to NUnit<ept id=\"p1\">](http://www.florian-rappl.de/News/Page/275/convert-mstest-to-nunit)</ept>","source":"[Blog post about migrating from MSTest to NUnit](http://www.florian-rappl.de/News/Page/275/convert-mstest-to-nunit)"},{"pos":[20039,20097],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>MSTest<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/ms243147.aspx)</ept>","source":"[MSTest](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/ms243147.aspx)"},{"pos":[20102,20133],"content":"Recommended Approach to Porting","linkify":"Recommended Approach to Porting","nodes":[{"content":"Recommended Approach to Porting","pos":[0,31]}]},{"content":"Finally, porting the code itself!","pos":[20135,20168]},{"content":"Ultimately, the actual porting effort will depend heavily on how your .NET Framework code is structured.","pos":[20169,20273]},{"content":"That being said, here is a recommended approach which may work well with your codebase.","pos":[20274,20361]},{"content":"A good way to port your code is to begin with the \"base\" of your library.","pos":[20363,20436]},{"content":"This may be data models or some other foundational classes and methods that everything else uses directly or indirectly.","pos":[20437,20557]},{"content":"Port the test project which tests the layer of your library that you're currently porting.","pos":[20562,20652]},{"content":"Copy over the \"base\" of your library into a new .NET Core project and select the version of the .NET Standard you wish to support.","pos":[20656,20786]},{"content":"Make any changes needed to get the code to compile.","pos":[20790,20841]},{"content":"Much of this may require adding NuGet package dependencies to your <ph id=\"ph1\">`project.json`</ph> file.","pos":[20842,20929],"source":" Much of this may require adding NuGet package dependencies to your `project.json` file."},{"content":"Run tests and make any needed adjustments.","pos":[20933,20975]},{"content":"Pick the next layer of code to port over and repeat steps 2 and 3!","pos":[20979,21045]},{"content":"If you methodically move outward from the base of your library and test each layer as needed, porting will be a systematic process where problems are isolated to one layer of code at a time.","pos":[21047,21237]}]}